<p>A <strong>gradient</strong> blends smoothly from one color to another. There's a catch that trips everyone up once: <code>background-color</code> only holds solid colors. Gradients go in the bigger <code>background</code> property:</p>

<pre><code class="css">body {
  background: linear-gradient(lightskyblue, plum);
  min-height: 100vh;
}</code></pre>

<p>First color at the top, fading to the second at the bottom &mdash; a sunset in one line of code. The second line matters too: your body is only as tall as your words, and a gradient that runs out part-way down the window starts over from the top color &mdash; leaving a strange band at the bottom. <code>min-height: 100vh</code> stretches the body to at least the full window (<code>vh</code> is short for <em>viewport height</em>, and 100 is all of it), so the sky always reaches the ground.</p>

<p>You can steer the gradient, too:</p>

<ul class="lesson-List">
  <li><code>linear-gradient(gold, orangered)</code> &mdash; warm dawn</li>
  <li><code>linear-gradient(to right, #ffe9f0, #e6e6fa)</code> &mdash; sideways fade</li>
  <li><code>linear-gradient(midnightblue, black)</code> &mdash; nightfall</li>
  <li><code>linear-gradient(gold, hotpink, midnightblue)</code> &mdash; the full sunset</li>
</ul>

<div class="your-Turn">
